, delivered and appraised. This book –the first in the New Perspectives in Policy and Politics series - brings together world-leading scholars to reflect on the implications of some of these developments for the field of policy studies and the world of practice. First published as a special issue of Policy & Politics, the book offers critical reflections on the recent history and future direction of policy studies. It advances the debate by rethinking the ways in which scholars and students of policy studies can (re)engage with pertinent issues in pursuit of both scholarly excellence and practical solutions to global policy problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aPolicy sciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAyres, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyres, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCointre, Sara Le, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Jonathan Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenger, Menno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlinders, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuarneros-Meza, Valeria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohn, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLowndes, Vivien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarsh, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCaughie, Kerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeters, B. Guy